<DOC><DOCNO> AP900531-0170 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-90 2302EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Cocaine     05-31 0193</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Canada-Cocaine,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Two Colombians, 1 New Yorker Found Guilty in Cocaine Trial</HEAD><DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two Colombians and a New Yorker, captured inCanada's largest drug bust, were found guilty Thursday forconspiring to traffic cocaine worth about $200 million.   The three face a maximum life sentence. Sentencing is scheduledfor Monday.   Moments before the jury's verdict was announced, Ricardo DelgadoMarquez, 24, of New York, and Colombians Fernando William MendozaSalazar, 27, and Flor E. Mery-Correa, 32, were seen laughing in theprisoners' box.   The jury of nine men and three women deliberated for 15 daysbefore reaching its verdict.   The three were arrested April 1989 after undercover policeintercepted a shipment of 1,100 pounds of cocaine flown fromColombia to Montreal and replaced most of the drug with brown sugarin an elaborate sting operation.   Ms. Mery-Correa was found guilty of conspiracy to traffic incocaine and possession for the purpose of trafficking. She wasacquitted of conspiring to import and export the narcotic.   Delgado-Marquez and Mendoza-Salazar were convicted of conspiringto export and traffic cocaine and possession for the purpose oftrafficking, but were acquitted of conspiracy to import.</TEXT></DOC>